# Project Context

DataSense is an AI-powered chat interface for querying open datasets published on
data.gov.in. Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript, Groq LLM for generating responses.
Users sign in with Google or email/password and get persisted chat history. Users
are not limited to a fixed list of datasets — they can point the app at any
resource on data.gov.in by pasting its page URL or resource ID.

# Tech Stack

- Next.js (App Router), TypeScript (strict mode)
- Groq LLM API — calls happen server-side only, never from client components
- data.gov.in REST API — one API key (tied to the account, not the dataset) works
  for fetching ANY resource by `resource_id` (UUID). There is no public catalog
  search API on data.gov.in — resource IDs can only be obtained by a human finding
  a dataset's page and either reading the ID off it directly, or the server
  scraping that one page for UUID candidates and testing them (see "Dataset
  Resolution" below). Don't assume a keyword-search endpoint exists; it doesn't.
- Auth.js v5 (`next-auth`) — Google OAuth **and** a Credentials (email/password)
  provider. Session strategy is JWT (required for Credentials; it cannot use the
  database session strategy).
- bcryptjs for hashing passwords used by the Credentials provider.
- MongoDB via the **native `mongodb` driver** + `@auth/mongodb-adapter` — there is
  no Mongoose in this project. Don't introduce it.
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui (Radix primitives) for UI
- Zod for server env validation and (increasingly) API request body validation —
  schemas live in `src/schemas/`.

# Dataset Resolution (replaces the old fixed registry)

- Datasets are no longer a hardcoded 3-entry enum. A dataset is identified by its
  raw `resource_id` (UUID) — any valid one works with the existing API key.
- Users add a dataset to a conversation by either:
  1. Pasting a raw resource_id directly — validate by calling
     `api.data.gov.in/resource/{id}?limit=1`; if it returns records, it's valid.
  2. Pasting a data.gov.in dataset page URL — the server fetches that one page's
     HTML, regex-extracts UUID candidates (same approach as the existing
     `scripts/find-census-resource.mjs`), and tests each against the API until one
     returns records. This is a single-page fetch, not catalog-wide crawling.
- Resolved datasets (id, title from the API response's `title` field, portalUrl,
  field list, resolvedAt) are cached in a shared `datasets` collection in MongoDB so
  the same dataset isn't re-resolved on every message, and so one user resolving a
  dataset benefits everyone (an organically-grown shared library, not a per-user
  copy). This is a deliberate exception to "Mongo is only for users + chat
  history" — confirmed with the project owner because re-scraping a page on every
  chat message would be slow and fragile.
- There is no question-text auto-detection across unlimited datasets — that only
  worked when there were 3 known Census categories to regex-match against (the old
  `dataset-router.ts`). A conversation is now explicitly tied to whichever
  dataset(s) the user selected/added, not guessed from free text.

# Project Structure (actual, not aspirational)

- `src/app/api/*/route.ts` — one responsibility per route: `chat`, `conversations`,
  `conversations/[id]`, `datasets`, `datasets/resolve` (new — resolves a pasted
  URL/resource_id), `auth/[...nextauth]`, `auth/register` (new — credentials signup).
- `src/app/chat/` and `src/app/chat/[id]/` — chat pages.
- `src/components/datasense/` — chat UI, including `sidebar/DatasetPicker.tsx`
  (now also handles adding a new dataset by URL/ID, not just picking from 3).
- `src/components/marketing/` — logged-out landing page.
- `src/components/providers/` — ThemeProvider, AppProviders.
- `src/hooks/` — client hooks: `useChat`, `useConversations`.
- `src/lib/ai/` — `chat-service.ts` (orchestration), `prompts.ts` (system prompt
  builder). `dataset-router.ts` is removed/replaced — see "Dataset Resolution".
- `src/lib/conversations/` — `service.ts`, `stream.ts`, `types.ts`.
- `src/lib/data-gov-in/` — data.gov.in API client (`fetchDataGovResource`) plus a
  new resolver module for the URL/ID-to-resource_id flow.
- `src/lib/datasets/` — now reads/writes the shared MongoDB `datasets` cache
  instead of a hardcoded `DEFAULT_RESOURCES` map.
- `src/lib/groq/` — Groq API client + error mapping.
- `src/lib/mongodb.ts` + `src/lib/mongodb/collections.ts` — cached client,
  collection names/types (now includes `datasets`).
- `src/lib/env.ts` — Zod-validated server env. `src/lib/errors.ts` — `AppError`.
- `src/lib/api-response.ts` — shared `jsonError()` helper for API routes.
- `src/auth.config.ts` — Edge-safe config used by `middleware.ts`: callbacks,
  pages, and the Google provider only. **Must never** import bcrypt, the
  `mongodb` driver, or anything else Node-only — it runs on the Edge runtime.
- `src/auth.ts` — full config: spreads `authConfig`, adds the Mongo adapter, AND
  the Credentials provider (its `authorize()` queries MongoDB and calls
  `bcrypt.compare`, both Node-only). Credentials provider must be defined here,
  never in `auth.config.ts`.
- `src/middleware.ts` — protects `/chat/:path*`.
- `src/types/next-auth.d.ts` — extends `Session.user` with `id`.

# Conventions

- Server Components by default. Add `"use client"` only when needed.
- All Groq, data.gov.in, and database calls happen in `route.ts` handlers or
  `src/lib/` helpers — never in client components.
- Every API route checks the session via `auth()` first and returns 401 if
  missing — never trust a client-supplied user id.
- API routes return `{ error: string, code?: string }` via the shared
  `jsonError()` helper in `src/lib/api-response.ts` — don't redefine it locally.
- Request bodies are validated with Zod schemas from `src/schemas/`.
- Use `async/await`; avoid `.then()` chains.
- Keep route handlers thin — prompt construction, data shaping, and DB queries
  belong in `src/lib/`.
- Naming: PascalCase for components, camelCase for functions/variables.

# Data & Cost Awareness

- One API key works for any `resource_id` — don't gate dataset access behind a
  fixed list in code.
- LLM prompts trim dataset JSON to `CHAT_MAX_CONTEXT_CHARS` and cap chat history
  to the last few turns — keep new code consistent with this budget.
- Resolving a dataset from a pasted URL can require multiple HTTP calls (one page
  fetch + one API test per UUID candidate) — this should happen once per dataset
  (cached), not on every chat message.

# Avoid

- Don't add Mongoose — password users live in the same `users` collection the
  MongoDB adapter manages, with an extra `password` field (Mongo has no fixed
  schema).
- Don't add Express or a separate backend.
- Don't import `@/auth` into `middleware.ts` or other Edge-runtime code — use
  `@/auth.config` there instead.
- Don't assume email/password signup and Google sign-in on the same email
  auto-link — Auth.js doesn't do this by default; it's an explicit decision.
- Never log or return the password hash to the client.
- Don't hardcode API keys, resource_ids, model names, or the Mongo URI.
- Don't claim or build a "search all datasets by keyword" feature — no such API
  exists on data.gov.in. Dataset discovery is always: a human finds it on
  data.gov.in's own site, then pastes the URL or ID into DataSense.
- Don't re-add a fixed DatasetId enum/union type — resource IDs are arbitrary
  strings now (validate as UUID-shaped, not as a closed set).

# When Unsure

- If a request is ambiguous about where logic should live, ask before generating
  code.
- If a refactor changes an API route's response shape or headers, check
  `useChat.ts` / `useConversations.ts` first — they parse exact field names.
- If something requires persisting new data outside `users`, chat history, or the
  `datasets` cache described above, flag it and ask before adding a collection.
